hypothesis.hypothesis:
Inline a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB directly inside if_stage.sv (no separate
module to forget to instantiate). Use EX/MEM register signals for update in
core.sv so no new ex_stage outputs are needed. Only two combinational lines
in ex_stage.sv change—redirect and redirect_target—while the EX/MEM register
pc_next assignment is left verbatim so RVFI pc_wdata stays architecturally
correct.

1. Extend if_id_t and id_ex_t with a single logic predict_taken bit.
2. In if_stage.sv, declare three parallel arrays:
     btb_valid [0:15]
     btb_tag   [0:15][25:0]   // pc[31:6]
     btb_target[0:15][31:0]
   On reset clear all valid bits. Combinational read:
     btb_hit   = btb_valid[pc[5:2]] && (btb_tag[pc[5:2]] == pc[31:6]);
     btb_target_out = btb_target[pc[5:2]];
   PC selection:
     next_pc = redirect ? redirect_target
                      : (btb_hit ? btb_target_out : pc + 32'd4);
   IF/ID output:
     out.predict_taken = btb_hit && !(flush || redirect);
   Add three new input ports to if_stage:
     btb_update_en, btb_update_pc[31:0], btb_update_target[31:0]
   Register the write on the posedge clock when btb_update_en is asserted:
     btb_valid[btb_update_pc[5:2]]   <= 1'b1;
     btb_tag  [btb_update_pc[5:2]]   <= btb_update_pc[31:6];
     btb_target[btb_update_pc[5:2]]  <= btb_update_target;
3. In id_stage.sv, latch in.predict_taken into the ID/EX register.
4. In ex_stage.sv make ONLY the following combinational changes and
   DO NOT modify the always_ff block that writes reg_q.pc_next:
     // Redirect only when prediction ≠ actual outcome.
     assign redirect = ((branch_taken != in.predict_taken) ||
                        (in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.predict_taken))
                       && !misalign_fault;
     // Recovery target: if we predicted taken but the branch is not taken,
     // go to the fall-through PC+4; otherwise use the normal jump/branch
     // target.
     assign redirect_target =
       (in.predict_taken && !branch_taken && !in.ctrl.is_jump)
         ? (in.pc + 32'd4)
         : (in.ctrl.is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target);
   // CRITICAL: reg_q.pc_next must keep the baseline expression that uses
   // actual branch_taken / is_jump / jump_target, independent of predict_taken
   // or redirect. This preserves rvfi_pc_fwd correctness.
5. In core.sv derive BTB update straight from the EX/MEM register:
     logic btb_update_en;
     logic [31:0] btb_update_pc;
     logic [31:0] btb_update_target;
     assign btb_update_en = ex_mem_w.valid && !ex_mem_w.ctrl.is_illegal &&
       ((ex_mem_w.ctrl.is_branch && ex_mem_w.branch_taken) ||
        (ex_mem_w.ctrl.is_jump && !ex_mem_w.ctrl.is_jalr));
     assign btb_update_pc     = ex_mem_w.pc;
     assign btb_update_target = ex_mem_w.pc_next;
   Wire these to the new if_stage ports and pass predict_taken through the
   existing if_id_w / id_ex_w pipeline bundles.

Because the BTB is indexed by the PC register output, the read path is a
tiny distributed-RAM lookup with no instruction-decode or adder on the
critical imem_data path. The 16-entry size keeps LUT/FF cost low so Fmax
impact should be negligible; meanwhile every correctly predicted taken branch
or JAL removes two full bubble cycles.
